1
00:00:25,434 --> 00:00:28,369
For as long as I can remember,

2
00:00:28,437 --> 00:00:30,428
I've been drawn to sharks.

3
00:00:30,506 --> 00:00:34,738
They're the most amazing
and mysterious animal on Earth.

4
00:00:34,810 --> 00:00:38,974
I thought if I studied them,
I could learn about life.

5
00:00:39,048 --> 00:00:43,542
About balance in the ocean
and how to survive on Earth.

6
00:00:43,619 --> 00:00:46,782
That the one animal
that we fear the most

7
00:00:46,856 --> 00:00:49,653
is the one we can't live without.

8
00:01:26,394 --> 00:01:28,328
Predator of the sea,

9
00:01:28,396 --> 00:01:32,127
terror of all men
who enter the ocean,

10
00:01:32,200 --> 00:01:34,862
the very symbol
of lurking danger:

11
00:01:34,936 --> 00:01:36,597
That is the shark.

12
00:02:04,064 --> 00:02:05,554
What is he really?

13
00:02:05,632 --> 00:02:08,123
We know little,
except the shark was here

14
00:02:08,202 --> 00:02:10,397
before the continents
took their present form,

15
00:02:10,470 --> 00:02:13,564
before the dinosaur lived,
and he is still here,

16
00:02:13,640 --> 00:02:15,335
essentially unchanged.

17
00:02:15,409 --> 00:02:18,003
One of the oldest living things
on Earth.

18
00:02:39,065 --> 00:02:41,158
How has the shark survived,

19
00:02:41,234 --> 00:02:44,226
when almost all that lived
in the beginnings

20
00:02:44,303 --> 00:02:46,203
has either perished or changed?

21
00:03:00,653 --> 00:03:04,020
Man must know all there is to know
about this enemy.

22
00:03:06,626 --> 00:03:08,651
Whether the shark
is really an enemy.

23
00:03:08,728 --> 00:03:09,990
If he is,

24
00:03:10,062 --> 00:03:12,326
how to protect against him.

25
00:03:12,398 --> 00:03:13,796
If he isn't,

26
00:03:13,865 --> 00:03:16,356
how to live with him.

27
00:03:45,964 --> 00:03:48,956
- You're told your whole life,
since you're a kid,

28
00:03:49,034 --> 00:03:50,968
sharks are dangerous.

29
00:03:51,036 --> 00:03:53,834
You're warned about venturing
too far into the ocean,

30
00:03:53,905 --> 00:03:56,135
but then finally
you're underwater,

31
00:03:56,207 --> 00:03:59,233
and you see the thing
you were taught

32
00:03:59,311 --> 00:04:02,006
your whole life to fear,
and it's perfect,

33
00:04:02,079 --> 00:04:04,479
and it doesn't want to hurt you,

34
00:04:04,548 --> 00:04:08,450
and it's the most beautiful thing
you've ever seen,

35
00:04:08,519 --> 00:04:11,215
and your whole world changes.

36
00:04:26,270 --> 00:04:29,296
Ever since I was little,
I've loved the ocean.

37
00:04:29,373 --> 00:04:32,103
Like many kids,
I tried fishing,

38
00:04:32,176 --> 00:04:37,136
but realized I was much happier
swimming with fish than catching them.

39
00:04:37,214 --> 00:04:39,409
Sharks were my favourite animals
on Earth,

40
00:04:39,483 --> 00:04:41,383
but all I'd heard about

41
00:04:41,452 --> 00:04:43,010
was how dangerous they were.

42
00:04:43,087 --> 00:04:46,181
I hated being afraid
and realized the only way

43
00:04:46,256 --> 00:04:50,817
to find out the truth about sharks
was to meet one for myself.

44
00:04:52,695 --> 00:04:54,629
I became
an underwater photographer

45
00:04:54,697 --> 00:04:56,790
and a biologist,

46
00:04:56,866 --> 00:04:59,960
and from that point on,
I followed sharks.

47
00:05:00,036 --> 00:05:03,164
So little is known
about what they really are

48
00:05:03,239 --> 00:05:06,140
and how important they are
to life on Earth.

49
00:05:09,679 --> 00:05:13,012
Two-thirds of the world's surface
is water,

50
00:05:13,082 --> 00:05:15,642
and over 80º/º of life on Earth

51
00:05:15,718 --> 00:05:17,709
lives in the ocean.

52
00:05:17,787 --> 00:05:21,279
I learned to dive
so I could get close to sharks,

53
00:05:21,357 --> 00:05:25,020
but photographing sharks
was harder than I thought.

54
00:05:26,963 --> 00:05:28,863
They're so afraid of us.

55
00:05:30,833 --> 00:05:34,701
Sharks can see us
with more than their eyes.

56
00:05:34,771 --> 00:05:37,239
They can sense our energy,

57
00:05:37,306 --> 00:05:40,797
and they viewed me as a threat.

58
00:05:47,048 --> 00:05:51,542
Sharks have been here
for more than 400 million years,

59
00:05:51,620 --> 00:05:55,579
150 million years
before the dinosaurs,

60
00:05:55,657 --> 00:05:58,524
when life had just begun on land.

61
00:05:58,593 --> 00:06:01,721
There was little oxygen
in the atmosphere,

62
00:06:01,797 --> 00:06:03,594
and only two continents.

63
00:06:03,665 --> 00:06:07,465
Sharks were shaping this world.

64
00:06:07,536 --> 00:06:11,666
Life on Earth
evolved from the sea.

65
00:06:11,740 --> 00:06:15,471
The first animals were tiny,
single-celled organisms

66
00:06:15,544 --> 00:06:18,308
that gave rise to algae, coral,

67
00:06:18,380 --> 00:06:20,848
and tiny planktonic animals.

68
00:06:23,685 --> 00:06:27,814
More invertebrates followed,
including squids and mollusks.

69
00:06:29,590 --> 00:06:32,559
One of the first vertebrates
with jaws,

70
00:06:32,626 --> 00:06:35,254
and the only large animal
that's remained unchanged

71
00:06:35,329 --> 00:06:37,991
for 400 million years,

72
00:06:38,065 --> 00:06:40,033
is the shark.

73
00:06:41,769 --> 00:06:46,934
New animals to evolve in the ocean
have been shaped by their predators,

74
00:06:47,007 --> 00:06:48,907
the sharks,

75
00:06:48,976 --> 00:06:51,877
giving rise to schooling behaviour,

76
00:06:51,946 --> 00:06:54,881
camouflage, speed,
size and communication.

77
00:06:54,949 --> 00:06:58,180
Sharks control
the populations below them,

78
00:06:58,252 --> 00:07:01,050
eliminating species
that were easy prey

79
00:07:01,121 --> 00:07:02,986
and creating new ones.

80
00:07:05,326 --> 00:07:07,886
Even though sharks
have very few young

81
00:07:07,962 --> 00:07:11,728
and take up to 25 years
to reach sexual maturity,

82
00:07:11,799 --> 00:07:16,394
they've managed to survive
through five major extinctions

83
00:07:16,469 --> 00:07:18,994
that wiped most life
from the planet.

84
00:07:19,072 --> 00:07:21,666
They're architects of our world.

85
00:07:23,176 --> 00:07:25,269
Most of what people
know about sharks

86
00:07:25,345 --> 00:07:28,246
they've heard from the media.

87
00:07:28,314 --> 00:07:30,248
The more time I spent with sharks,

88
00:07:30,316 --> 00:07:33,979
the more I realized that they're
nothing like what we're told.

89
00:07:34,053 --> 00:07:35,645
They are perfect predators

90
00:07:35,722 --> 00:07:38,748
that hold the underwater world
in balance,

91
00:07:38,825 --> 00:07:42,022
the lions and tigers of the seas.

92
00:07:43,396 --> 00:07:45,728
I spent so much time underwater

93
00:07:45,798 --> 00:07:48,062
so I could gain their trust

94
00:07:48,134 --> 00:07:50,830
and get close enough
to film them.

95
00:07:56,743 --> 00:07:59,610
Everything moved together,

96
00:07:59,679 --> 00:08:01,613
lived together,

97
00:08:01,681 --> 00:08:04,649
and died with a purpose.

98
00:08:14,593 --> 00:08:16,618
This shark and his relatives

99
00:08:16,695 --> 00:08:20,290
are long-established
enemies of man.

100
00:08:20,365 --> 00:08:23,960
He is a wicked,
unpredictable opponent.

101
00:08:24,036 --> 00:08:26,664
If sharks are in the area,

102
00:08:26,738 --> 00:08:28,365
you can repel them with sounds,

103
00:08:28,440 --> 00:08:30,670
by striking the surface of the water

104
00:08:30,742 --> 00:08:32,801
with your cupped hand.

105
00:08:32,878 --> 00:08:35,005
Or you can shout underwater.

106
00:08:43,221 --> 00:08:45,519
Among the visual methods
of preventing attacks

107
00:08:45,591 --> 00:08:47,582
are directing a stream of bubbles

108
00:08:47,659 --> 00:08:49,957
from your life preserver
in his direction.

109
00:08:52,063 --> 00:08:54,998
Tearing up paper
into small pieces

110
00:08:55,066 --> 00:08:56,533
and scattering them

111
00:08:56,601 --> 00:08:58,125
all around the raft.

112
00:09:01,272 --> 00:09:04,332
If a shark threatens to attack you
or damage the raft,

113
00:09:04,408 --> 00:09:06,808
do not try to shoot or knife him.

114
00:09:08,312 --> 00:09:11,713
Chances are you would only
slightly injure and infuriate him.

115
00:09:11,782 --> 00:09:14,376
Remember,

116
00:09:14,452 --> 00:09:17,421
his front end
is practically all mouth.

117
00:09:17,488 --> 00:09:18,853
Once in your raft,

118
00:09:18,923 --> 00:09:21,858
stay there and remain quiet.

119
00:09:21,926 --> 00:09:24,156
Remember that as a human being,

120
00:09:24,228 --> 00:09:27,755
you are smarter than a shark,
if you use your head.

121
00:09:32,336 --> 00:09:36,170
- Elephants kill more people
each year than sharks do,

122
00:09:36,240 --> 00:09:39,538
so there's some deep-seated
psychological revulsion

123
00:09:39,609 --> 00:09:43,773
about a cold-eyed monster
coming out of the deep

124
00:09:43,847 --> 00:09:46,543
and picking you to pieces,
but that is the myth, not the reality.

125
00:09:46,616 --> 00:09:50,052
- It's weird that white sharks
have such a bad reputation,

126
00:09:50,120 --> 00:09:52,987
because they really hardly bite.

127
00:09:53,056 --> 00:09:55,786
If we go into the statistics,
they are not the ones

128
00:09:55,859 --> 00:09:57,156
who bite the most.
Definitely not.

129
00:09:57,227 --> 00:09:59,661
And it's very hard, actually,
to approach a white shark.

130
00:09:59,729 --> 00:10:02,630
It's much easier to repel him
than to actually lure him in,

131
00:10:02,699 --> 00:10:04,462
bring him in,
and then trying to interact.

132
00:10:04,534 --> 00:10:06,968
So I think the main reason
why people are still afraid

133
00:10:07,037 --> 00:10:09,232
of a white shark
is based on the movie Jaws,

134
00:10:09,305 --> 00:10:13,071
and the misconception
is still floating around.

135
00:10:13,143 --> 00:10:16,909
And I think a big part
of the media still tries

136
00:10:16,980 --> 00:10:19,710
to present the white shark
as Jaws.

137
00:10:33,629 --> 00:10:35,927
- Three people were hurt Saturday
in another shark attack.

138
00:10:47,543 --> 00:10:50,740
- Time magazine is calling
it the "Summer of the Shark. "

139
00:10:55,217 --> 00:10:57,742
- And of course the question
being asked by some is:

140
00:10:57,820 --> 00:11:00,380
When will it be safe
to return to the water?

141
00:11:03,692 --> 00:11:07,651
- We love to have a monster,
we love to hate. So...

142
00:11:07,730 --> 00:11:10,164
And it's not good television

143
00:11:10,232 --> 00:11:13,827
if, you know, this monster
that we presented all these years

144
00:11:13,902 --> 00:11:16,597
actually is a very shy, hesitant animal

145
00:11:16,671 --> 00:11:21,005
that has a hard time,
like any other animal as well.

146
00:11:21,075 --> 00:11:22,440
So we like to have the monster,

147
00:11:22,510 --> 00:11:24,535
and that's why
it's still portrayed this way.

148
00:11:32,253 --> 00:11:33,914
I was on an assignment,

149
00:11:33,988 --> 00:11:36,388
photographing
the Galapagos Islands,

150
00:11:36,457 --> 00:11:38,186
600 miles from Ecuador,

151
00:11:38,259 --> 00:11:41,456
in the middle of the Pacific,

152
00:11:41,529 --> 00:11:43,121
in total isolation

153
00:11:43,197 --> 00:11:45,324
from the rest of the world.

154
00:11:46,534 --> 00:11:48,161
It's a world heritage site,

155
00:11:48,236 --> 00:11:52,002
full of species
found nowhere else on Earth.

156
00:11:53,608 --> 00:11:56,133
This is where Charles Darwin

157
00:11:56,210 --> 00:11:58,770
developed his theory of evolution.

158
00:11:58,846 --> 00:12:02,804
What I believe
is the whole planet was like this.

159
00:12:02,883 --> 00:12:05,943
I think animals
were amazingly abundant;

160
00:12:06,019 --> 00:12:08,351
I think whales
were amazingly abundant,

161
00:12:08,421 --> 00:12:12,755
fish were amazingly abundant;
turtles, birds, everything,

162
00:12:12,826 --> 00:12:15,659
before man got in there

163
00:12:15,729 --> 00:12:18,994
and really hacked
the whole thing to pieces.

164
00:12:19,065 --> 00:12:23,798
- I travelled 160 miles
from the centre of the Galapagos

165
00:12:23,870 --> 00:12:26,202
to Darwin and Wolf,

166
00:12:26,273 --> 00:12:28,605
two remote undersea volcanoes

167
00:12:28,675 --> 00:12:31,940
that barely broke the surface.

168
00:12:32,012 --> 00:12:33,946
One of the few places on Earth

169
00:12:34,014 --> 00:12:38,007
where hammerhead sharks
congregate in schools.

170
00:12:41,121 --> 00:12:43,715
We're just getting ready
to go in for a dive

171
00:12:43,790 --> 00:12:46,884
where there's supposed to be
congregating hammerhead sharks.

172
00:12:46,960 --> 00:12:48,757
The undersea currents come up,

173
00:12:48,829 --> 00:12:50,921
bringing nutrient-rich water
to the surface,

174
00:12:50,996 --> 00:12:54,329
which causes a ton
of tiny plankton feeders to school here,

175
00:12:54,400 --> 00:12:56,800
and the hammerhead sharks
come up as well,

176
00:12:56,869 --> 00:12:58,632
and they circle in the current

177
00:12:58,704 --> 00:13:01,730
and go back down at night
to feed on squid.

178
00:13:01,807 --> 00:13:04,002
So we're gonna go down
to maybe 130 feet

179
00:13:04,076 --> 00:13:06,340
and see if we can find
some schooling hammerhead sharks,

180
00:13:06,412 --> 00:13:08,312
possibly a silky shark or two.

181
00:13:11,150 --> 00:13:13,084
The Galapagos hosts

182
00:13:13,152 --> 00:13:15,882
one of the largest marine
reserves on Earth,

183
00:13:15,955 --> 00:13:18,685
where sharks
are cherished and protected.

184
00:13:20,593 --> 00:13:24,290
Hammerheads are some
of the most misunderstood species.

185
00:13:24,363 --> 00:13:27,457
They are incredibly shy animals.

186
00:13:27,533 --> 00:13:29,194
Hammerheads, like all sharks,

187
00:13:29,268 --> 00:13:31,828
have two more senses than people.

188
00:13:31,904 --> 00:13:36,671
They have lateral lines
running along the sides of their bodies,

189
00:13:36,742 --> 00:13:38,710
that can detect movement
in the water.

190
00:13:40,478 --> 00:13:43,538
Their heads
are a giant sensory system

191
00:13:43,615 --> 00:13:45,776
that detects electro-magnetic fields,

192
00:13:45,850 --> 00:13:50,287
enabling them to find food
that's hidden from view

193
00:13:50,355 --> 00:13:52,585
and to feel my heartbeat.

194
00:13:52,657 --> 00:13:54,147
They can feel me

195
00:13:54,225 --> 00:13:57,319
and know if I'm excited or scared.

196
00:13:58,963 --> 00:14:00,794
They're so afraid of us,

197
00:14:00,865 --> 00:14:02,730
that if I'm not calm,

198
00:14:02,800 --> 00:14:04,734
keeping my heart rate low,

199
00:14:04,802 --> 00:14:06,997
they won't come
anywhere near me.

200
00:14:16,848 --> 00:14:19,817
Hammerheads use
the Earth's magnetic field

201
00:14:19,884 --> 00:14:22,876
to follow undersea ridges
like road maps,

202
00:14:22,954 --> 00:14:26,515
navigating thousands of miles
through the oceans.

203
00:14:29,059 --> 00:14:30,686
Sharks are normally solitary,

204
00:14:30,761 --> 00:14:32,422
but hammerheads come together

205
00:14:32,496 --> 00:14:35,431
only at a few undersea pinnacles

206
00:14:35,499 --> 00:14:37,797
to socialize and mate.

207
00:14:39,870 --> 00:14:43,033
The schools are made up
of mostly females,

208
00:14:43,106 --> 00:14:46,598
with the largest vying
for position in the centre,

209
00:14:46,677 --> 00:14:48,975
where the males come
to look for mates.

210
00:14:50,681 --> 00:14:53,172
Dominant females,
which can be 12 feet long,

211
00:14:53,250 --> 00:14:55,184
control their position in the school

212
00:14:55,252 --> 00:14:56,947
using aggressive displays,

213
00:14:57,020 --> 00:15:00,046
pushing subordinate females
to the fringes.

214
00:15:02,059 --> 00:15:04,186
The schools break up at night,

215
00:15:04,261 --> 00:15:07,162
when they descend
into deeper water to feed.

216
00:15:07,230 --> 00:15:09,494
We know so little about sharks

217
00:15:09,566 --> 00:15:11,966
that a new species of hammerhead

218
00:15:12,035 --> 00:15:15,663
was just found
in the Atlantic Ocean in 2006.

219
00:15:18,708 --> 00:15:20,471
The shape of their head

220
00:15:20,543 --> 00:15:23,774
makes them one of the most
manoeuvrable and feared sharks.

221
00:15:23,846 --> 00:15:25,279
But the truth is,

222
00:15:25,348 --> 00:15:27,646
there's no record
of a hammerhead shark

223
00:15:27,717 --> 00:15:29,344
ever killing anyone.

224
00:15:58,414 --> 00:16:00,541
When we surfaced from the dive,

225
00:16:00,616 --> 00:16:02,413
we found two fishing boats

226
00:16:02,485 --> 00:16:05,317
trailing 60 miles of long lines.

227
00:16:07,255 --> 00:16:10,782
A line with 16,000 baited hooks

228
00:16:10,859 --> 00:16:14,955
that would stretch from Earth
to outer space.

229
00:16:17,999 --> 00:16:19,933
The boats fled,

230
00:16:20,001 --> 00:16:23,300
because long-line fishing
is illegal in the Galapagos,

231
00:16:23,371 --> 00:16:26,067
and we were left with the lines.

232
00:16:29,577 --> 00:16:31,807
I hopped in the water
as soon as I could

233
00:16:31,880 --> 00:16:33,905
and brought my cameras in
and tried to film,

234
00:16:33,982 --> 00:16:35,813
whatever I could find
on the long lines,

235
00:16:35,884 --> 00:16:38,011
and we swam for probably
two or three kilometres,

236
00:16:38,086 --> 00:16:39,451
pulling ourselves along the lines,

237
00:16:39,521 --> 00:16:42,957
and unclipping
every baited hook we could find.

238
00:16:43,024 --> 00:16:46,585
The first fish I found
was a seven-foot-long sailfish,

239
00:16:46,661 --> 00:16:49,129
and it was dead.

240
00:16:49,197 --> 00:16:52,757
It suffocated because it wrapped itself
up in the long line.

241
00:16:52,833 --> 00:16:55,802
So it couldn't keep swimming
to keep breathing.

242
00:16:59,139 --> 00:17:02,006
Farther along the line,
I found a dorado.

243
00:17:02,076 --> 00:17:03,600
It was still alive.

244
00:17:03,677 --> 00:17:06,305
It was swimming in a circle,

245
00:17:06,380 --> 00:17:08,109
the largest it could

246
00:17:08,182 --> 00:17:11,310
considering the long line
attached to it.

247
00:17:14,822 --> 00:17:18,121
I slowly pulled myself close
so I wouldn't scare it,

248
00:17:18,192 --> 00:17:19,659
and I cut it loose.

249
00:17:29,369 --> 00:17:31,997
Then I found the sharks.

250
00:17:37,444 --> 00:17:39,241
For 60 miles,

251
00:17:39,313 --> 00:17:41,746
sharks were dying on those lines.

252
00:17:43,149 --> 00:17:45,117
They struggle so much

253
00:17:45,184 --> 00:17:48,585
that they entangle themselves
and suffocate.

254
00:17:48,654 --> 00:17:50,918
There were only a few left alive,

255
00:17:50,990 --> 00:17:52,617
and I cut them loose.

256
00:17:55,695 --> 00:17:57,094
In total,

257
00:17:57,163 --> 00:17:58,630
we found 160 sharks,

