01:04:11,410 --> 01:04:14,902
looking for the silhouette
of a seal -

1003
01:04:14,980 --> 01:04:19,280
a very similar silhouette
to a human on the surface.

1004
01:04:19,751 --> 01:04:22,219
A healthy seal
moves through the water

1005
01:04:22,287 --> 01:04:24,084
without any noise or bubbles.

1006
01:04:24,156 --> 01:04:26,215
But an injured one
will flail about,

1007
01:04:26,291 --> 01:04:28,088
creating a disturbance
in the water,

1008
01:04:28,160 --> 01:04:32,096
just like humans when we swim.

1009
01:04:32,164 --> 01:04:35,793
It's amazing how few people
are attacked each year,

1010
01:04:35,868 --> 01:04:38,769
considering how much
we look like shark food.

1011
01:04:38,837 --> 01:04:41,237
- We treat animals differently,
but they're all doing the same thing.

1012
01:04:41,306 --> 01:04:44,366
So the cute little baby harp seal
grows up and goes out and eats fish,

1013
01:04:44,443 --> 01:04:46,809
just as viciously as a shark.

1014
01:04:46,879 --> 01:04:49,871
But we think of the seal
as sort of cute and cuddly,

1015
01:04:49,948 --> 01:04:52,178
and we think of the shark
as something vicious,

1016
01:04:52,251 --> 01:04:53,741
but that's just human mythology.

1017
01:05:26,117 --> 01:05:28,415
Then my mission stopped cold,

1018
01:05:28,486 --> 01:05:31,944
I had a pain in my leg
and was taken to the hospital.

1019
01:05:33,491 --> 01:05:35,982
It was diagnosed
as flesh-eating disease.

1020
01:05:36,060 --> 01:05:38,927
Doctors said
I was lucky to be alive,

1021
01:05:38,996 --> 01:05:41,191
that I would only lose my leg.

1022
01:05:43,634 --> 01:05:47,000
I had a pain in my lymph gland
to the right of -

1023
01:05:47,070 --> 01:05:48,799
to the left of my groin -

1024
01:05:48,872 --> 01:05:52,171
and I came to the hospital,
asked them what's wrong;

1025
01:05:52,242 --> 01:05:56,906
they said I got Staphylococcal
bacteria in my leg.

1026
01:05:56,980 --> 01:06:00,279
Staphylococcus,
or flesh-eating disease,

1027
01:06:00,350 --> 01:06:02,409
infects the body through any wound,

1028
01:06:02,485 --> 01:06:06,751
even a tiny cut,
like the ones I had on my feet.

1029
01:06:06,823 --> 01:06:10,088
It destroys tissue,
consuming the body,

1030
01:06:10,160 --> 01:06:13,425
and if untreated, can kill you.

1031
01:06:17,267 --> 01:06:20,430
I was hospitalized,
fighting to save my leg.

1032
01:06:22,472 --> 01:06:25,236
Watching the IV
of antibiotics and saline solution

1033
01:06:25,308 --> 01:06:27,208
drip into my arm.

1034
01:06:27,277 --> 01:06:30,678
Now that I couldn't be
in the ocean,

1035
01:06:30,747 --> 01:06:33,408
they were dripping the ocean
into me.

1036
01:06:36,151 --> 01:06:38,585
I'll be fine, okay?

1037
01:06:38,654 --> 01:06:40,747
I promise.

1038
01:06:40,823 --> 01:06:44,281
I lay there, watching the red line
creep up my leg.

1039
01:06:45,694 --> 01:06:49,721
It was halfway through my thigh
and if it made it to my hip,

1040
01:06:49,798 --> 01:06:52,892
I would lose more than my leg.

1041
01:06:54,937 --> 01:06:57,872
I'm probably way more likely
to die working in Toronto than here.

1042
01:07:04,146 --> 01:07:07,741
Dude... Brian, don't get stressed
and don't get upset, okay?

1043
01:07:09,284 --> 01:07:13,186
It's fine, it's just...
it's just another bump, alright?

1044
01:07:14,690 --> 01:07:17,124
Then I heard from Paul.

1045
01:07:17,192 --> 01:07:19,854
He said there was nothing
they could do,

1046
01:07:19,928 --> 01:07:23,363
Sea Shepherd was being
kicked out of the Galapagos...

1047
01:07:25,967 --> 01:07:29,425
...because the Galapagos
had legalized long-lining.

1048
01:07:32,040 --> 01:07:34,975
The fishermen wanted more money
and had turned to shark fins.

1049
01:07:35,043 --> 01:07:37,568
The government gave in,

1050
01:07:37,645 --> 01:07:40,808
and long-lining was legalized.

1051
01:07:41,749 --> 01:07:44,309
Now we've lost Cocos
and the Galapagos

1052
01:07:44,385 --> 01:07:46,376
to the fin industry.

1053
01:07:47,922 --> 01:07:51,016
I think the world needs to know

1054
01:07:51,092 --> 01:07:52,889
that sharks are probably

1055
01:07:52,960 --> 01:07:55,428
the most threatened
group of species

1056
01:07:55,496 --> 01:07:58,863
that we have
in the ocean right now.

1057
01:07:58,933 --> 01:08:01,993
And that a lot of shark species
are declining very rapidly;

1058
01:08:02,070 --> 01:08:04,937
that this is not
a natural phenomenon.

1059
01:08:05,006 --> 01:08:08,703
It's because of fishing
and other human impacts

1060
01:08:08,776 --> 01:08:14,577
and that there's a lot we can do
about this to change it.

1061
01:08:16,683 --> 01:08:19,846
- Sharks are going to be difficult
to conserve,

1062
01:08:19,920 --> 01:08:23,879
because on one hand,
you have people afraid of them

1063
01:08:23,957 --> 01:08:27,586
and not really wanting
to go anywhere near them.

1064
01:08:27,661 --> 01:08:30,221
People can sort of fish them
with impunity.

1065
01:08:30,297 --> 01:08:32,561
There's nobody
looking after the sharks.

1066
01:08:32,632 --> 01:08:34,395
There's no campaign,

1067
01:08:34,468 --> 01:08:36,231
like a Greenpeace campaign,

1068
01:08:36,303 --> 01:08:38,100
to save the sharks.

1069
01:10:40,624 --> 01:10:43,286
Paul left to start a campaign

1070
01:10:43,360 --> 01:10:46,386
against illegal whaling
in Antarctica.

1071
01:10:46,730 --> 01:10:48,925
And I was alone.

1072
01:10:50,867 --> 01:10:54,030
Two of the world's
last sanctuaries for sharks

1073
01:10:54,104 --> 01:10:56,231
were going to be wiped out.

1074
01:10:56,306 --> 01:10:59,070
During my last six days
in the hospital,

1075
01:10:59,142 --> 01:11:02,270
more than 1.5 million sharks
had been killed.

1076
01:11:03,647 --> 01:11:06,207
Everyone told me to go home,

1077
01:11:06,283 --> 01:11:07,511
forget about sharks,

1078
01:11:07,584 --> 01:11:10,178
and try and save my leg.

1079
01:11:10,254 --> 01:11:14,520
I didn't know if what I was doing
made sense anymore,

1080
01:11:14,591 --> 01:11:16,684
but all I could think about

1081
01:11:16,760 --> 01:11:18,887
was getting back underwater
with sharks.

1082
01:11:24,367 --> 01:11:27,268
Sharks' presence in the ocean
has provided a framework

1083
01:11:27,336 --> 01:11:29,600
for the populations below them,

1084
01:11:29,672 --> 01:11:31,299
including phytoplankton,

1085
01:11:31,374 --> 01:11:34,343
tiny aquatic plants
that consume more carbon dioxide

1086
01:11:34,410 --> 01:11:36,173
than anything else on Earth.

1087
01:11:36,245 --> 01:11:38,975
Carbon dioxide
is the global-warming gas,

1088
01:11:39,048 --> 01:11:41,380
and plankton converts it to oxygen,

1089
01:11:41,450 --> 01:11:45,045
providing 70º/º of the oxygen
we breathe on land.

1090
01:11:45,121 --> 01:11:47,021
Without sharks to prey on them,

1091
01:11:47,089 --> 01:11:49,956
plankton feeders below sharks
could grow out of control,

1092
01:11:50,026 --> 01:11:52,927
consuming the plankton
that we depend on for survival.

1093
01:11:54,463 --> 01:11:57,023
The ocean
is the most important ecosystem,

1094
01:11:57,099 --> 01:12:01,195
regulating climate
and feeding much of the planet.

1095
01:12:01,270 --> 01:12:04,603
Life on land
depends on life in the ocean.

1096
01:12:05,775 --> 01:12:09,835
I finally realized
that it's not just about saving sharks,

1097
01:12:09,911 --> 01:12:12,675
it's about saving ourselves.

1098
01:12:15,650 --> 01:12:18,744
There was nothing I could do
to save sharks in the Galapagos,

1099
01:12:18,820 --> 01:12:21,983
but shark finning
was still illegal in Costa Rica.

1100
01:12:22,057 --> 01:12:24,525
If I could get back
into Costa Rica,

1101
01:12:24,592 --> 01:12:26,719
maybe I could finally
get to Cocos

1102
01:12:26,795 --> 01:12:28,956
and do something
to stop the finning.

1103
01:12:30,498 --> 01:12:33,262
I lay there,
hoping the red line would stop,

1104
01:12:33,335 --> 01:12:35,803
and after a week it did.

1105
01:12:36,638 --> 01:12:40,199
The infection subsided
and I was finally free.

1106
01:12:41,910 --> 01:12:43,639
I think the problem is,

1107
01:12:43,712 --> 01:12:46,875
that we don't really understand
what we are.

1108
01:12:46,948 --> 01:12:50,247
In essence,
we're, uh, you know,

1109
01:12:50,318 --> 01:12:52,684
just a conceited naked ape,

1110
01:12:52,754 --> 01:12:55,882
but in our minds
we're some sort of divine legend

1111
01:12:55,957 --> 01:12:59,551
and we see ourselves
as some sort of god,

1112
01:12:59,626 --> 01:13:04,029
that we can walk around the Earth
deciding who will live and who will die,

1113
01:13:04,098 --> 01:13:06,999
and what will be destroyed
and what will be saved.

1114
01:13:07,067 --> 01:13:11,197
But the fact is, we're just a bunch
of primates out of control.

1115
01:13:30,791 --> 01:13:33,692
We're now in the midst
of a Third World War,

1116
01:13:33,761 --> 01:13:35,592
but this time
the enemy is ourselves

1117
01:13:35,662 --> 01:13:38,825
and the objective is to save
the planet from ourselves.

1118
01:13:38,899 --> 01:13:41,766
There is no hope
for the masses of humanity

1119
01:13:41,835 --> 01:13:43,268
to do anything.

1120
01:13:43,337 --> 01:13:45,532
They never have, they never will.

1121
01:13:45,605 --> 01:13:49,507
All social change comes
from the passionate intervention

1122
01:13:49,575 --> 01:13:52,567
of individuals
or small groups of individuals.

1123
01:13:53,913 --> 01:13:57,110
Slavery wasn't ended
by any government or any institution.

1124
01:13:57,183 --> 01:13:59,947
Women got the right to vote

1125
01:14:00,019 --> 01:14:02,214
not because of any government.

1126
01:14:02,288 --> 01:14:06,691
The civil-rights movement,
the same thing -

1127
01:14:06,759 --> 01:14:10,695
India with Mahatma Gandhi,
South Africa with Nelson Mandela.

1128
01:14:10,763 --> 01:14:12,958
Again, it's always individuals.

1129
01:14:13,032 --> 01:14:14,795
You need those individuals

1130
01:14:14,867 --> 01:14:16,960
with the passion and the energy
to get involved.

1131
01:14:17,036 --> 01:14:18,765
In fact, I don't know

1132
01:14:18,838 --> 01:14:20,567
of any governments or institutions

1133
01:14:20,640 --> 01:14:22,938
that are doing anything
to solve any of these problems.

1134
01:14:24,243 --> 01:14:26,973
All over the world, though,
I am seeing individuals

1135
01:14:27,046 --> 01:14:29,514
and non-government organizations
that are passionately involved

1136
01:14:29,582 --> 01:14:33,177
in protecting ecosystems
and species,

1137
01:14:33,252 --> 01:14:35,685
and that's where I see
some optimism,

1138
01:14:35,754 --> 01:14:37,779
that's where results
are happening.

1139
01:14:59,077 --> 01:15:00,442
Okay...

1140
01:15:00,512 --> 01:15:01,945
here we go.

1141
01:15:02,013 --> 01:15:05,380
As soon as I was let out
of the hospital,

1142
01:15:05,450 --> 01:15:08,510
I started making my way
back to Costa Rica.

1143
01:15:08,587 --> 01:15:12,580
Costa Rica was the last place
on Earth I should go.

1144
01:15:12,657 --> 01:15:14,557
I would be arrested immediately

1145
01:15:14,626 --> 01:15:17,322
if they found out I was there.

1146
01:15:17,395 --> 01:15:19,886
So I had to sneak in.

1147
01:15:19,965 --> 01:15:22,432
I took a boat
from the Galapagos Islands

1148
01:15:22,500 --> 01:15:24,058
to mainland Ecuador.

1149
01:15:24,134 --> 01:15:26,102
My friends in Costa Rica

1150
01:15:26,170 --> 01:15:29,333
told me not to fly back
into the country,

1151
01:15:29,406 --> 01:15:32,239
that I'd be caught if I did.

1152
01:15:36,180 --> 01:15:38,171
I had to avoid any major ports,

1153
01:15:38,249 --> 01:15:40,581
the police and the Coast Guard.

1154
01:15:40,651 --> 01:15:42,812
Even if I made it to the coast,

1155
01:15:42,887 --> 01:15:45,617
I'd also have to avoid
the shark-fin Mafia.

1156
01:15:52,930 --> 01:15:54,557
To avoid capture,

1157
01:15:54,632 --> 01:15:56,532
I travelled overland for days,

1158
01:15:56,600 --> 01:15:58,898
using public transportation
and tour buses

1159
01:15:58,969 --> 01:16:01,335
to get back into the country.

1160
01:16:01,405 --> 01:16:03,873
Still going, this bus?

1161
01:16:03,941 --> 01:16:07,206
I only narrowly escaped arrest
a few weeks earlier,

1162
01:16:07,278 --> 01:16:09,871
but I had to find a way in

1163
01:16:09,946 --> 01:16:12,574
and find a way
to help the sharks.

1164
01:16:18,955 --> 01:16:21,753
Avoiding arrest and staying
on public buses,

1165
01:16:21,824 --> 01:16:24,224
I made it to the coast

1166
01:16:24,294 --> 01:16:26,922
and entered Puntarenas.

1167
01:16:33,803 --> 01:16:37,705
Instead of the shark-fin Mafia
I was expecting to greet me,

1168
01:16:37,774 --> 01:16:40,436
there were protests
in the streets.

1169
01:16:42,178 --> 01:16:45,636
Costa Ricans were rallying
against shark finning.

1170
01:16:45,715 --> 01:16:48,775
The publicity surrounding our case
brought the shark-finning industry

1171
01:16:48,851 --> 01:16:50,341
into the spotlight.

1172
01:16:50,420 --> 01:16:53,048
We hadn't totally failed
in saving sharks.

1173
01:16:54,724 --> 01:16:57,625
We helped awaken a country
and the people.

1174
01:16:59,161 --> 01:17:00,651
Costa Ricans were outraged;

1175
01:17:00,729 --> 01:17:04,290
they held protests
against the private docks

1176
01:17:04,366 --> 01:17:06,425
and spoke out
against the corruption.

1177
01:17:08,170 --> 01:17:10,730
The world had started
rallying for sharks.

1178
01:17:24,720 --> 01:17:27,655
The police were busy
with the protest

1179
01:17:27,723 --> 01:17:30,283
and the Mafia was in hiding.

1180
01:17:32,127 --> 01:17:35,426
Now I knew I could make it to Cocos
without getting caught.

1181
01:17:42,270 --> 01:17:45,467
I found my friends
and we headed back out to sea.

1182
01:18:02,723 --> 01:18:04,918
Returning underwater,

1183
01:18:04,992 --> 01:18:08,120
finally I could swim
with sharks again,

1184
01:18:08,195 --> 01:18:11,892
in one of the last places on Earth
where sharks thrive.

1185
01:18:14,435 --> 01:18:17,199
Free diving...

1186
01:18:17,271 --> 01:18:19,705
I hold my breath and stay calm

1187
01:18:19,774 --> 01:18:22,242
so they're not afraid of me.

1188
01:18:27,615 --> 01:18:29,947
Ever since I was a kid,

1189
01:18:30,017 --> 01:18:31,575
I've loved sharks.

1190
01:18:36,790 --> 01:18:39,054
They taught me about life,

1191
01:18:39,125 --> 01:18:42,458
and that fear
was something I made up,

1192
01:18:42,529 --> 01:18:44,588
and it wasn't real.

1193
01:18:48,501 --> 01:18:51,993
Sharks have been here
since the beginning,

1194
01:18:52,072 --> 01:18:55,064
when there was only primitive life
in the oceans

1195
01:18:55,141 --> 01:18:57,871
and the land was mostly desert.

1196
01:18:59,646 --> 01:19:02,012
They were the top predator,

1197
01:19:02,082 --> 01:19:05,381
influencing any animal to evolve
since their inception.

1198
01:19:08,588 --> 01:19:10,886
Sharks have been gods

1199
01:19:10,957 --> 01:19:13,255
for 400 million years,

1200
01:19:13,326 --> 01:19:15,021
shaping this world

1201
01:19:15,095 --> 01:19:18,724
for the entire history
of life on land.

1202
01:19:24,403 --> 01:19:26,098
Seeing them again,

1203
01:19:26,171 --> 01:19:28,901
I knew that they're almost gone.

1204
01:19:31,276 --> 01:19:32,766
The killing of sharks

1205
01:19:32,845 --> 01:19:36,804
is the biggest ecological time bomb
we're going to face pretty soon.

1206
01:19:36,882 --> 01:19:39,646
We have to understand
that sharks are the most abundant

1207
01:19:39,718 --> 01:19:42,209
top predator on this planet,
at over 100 pounds,

1208
01:19:42,287 --> 01:19:45,347
so that tells you something.
Nature created them for a reason.

1209
01:19:45,424 --> 01:19:47,619
Now human beings just...
they don't care

1210
01:19:47,693 --> 01:19:50,457
they kill 100 million, 200 million.
"So what?" You know?

1211
01:19:50,529 --> 01:19:53,589
"Sharks are a nuisance,
a dead shark is a good shark,

1212
01:19:53,665 --> 01:19:56,725
let's kill 'em all. "
But if we kill 'em all,

1213
01:19:56,802 --> 01:19:59,566
we destroy all food chains
of an entire marine ecosystem

1214
01:19:59,638 --> 01:20:02,698
and, well, the majority of our oxygen
comes from the ocean,

1215
01:20:02,775 --> 01:20:04,470
so we should be more careful.

1216
01:20:04,543 --> 01:20:07,808
- There is no species on this planet
that has ever survived

1217
01:20:07,880 --> 01:20:09,939
by ignoring
the basic laws of ecology,

1218
01:20:10,015 --> 01:20:13,882
and we're now breaking those basic laws
every day in every way,

1219
01:20:13,951 --> 01:20:18,718
and that's going to mean our own demise
in a very short period of time,

1220
01:20:18,790 --> 01:20:21,782
unless we learn to live harmoniously
with the natural world.

1221
01:20:21,859 --> 01:20:25,056
- Future generations
are gonna look back on us

1222
01:20:25,129 --> 01:20:28,724
and they're gonna think of us
as barbarians,

1223
01:20:28,800 --> 01:20:31,997
the same way
we think of slave traders.

1224
01:20:32,069 --> 01:20:36,130
That they're gonna look at us
as barbarians for what we're doing,

1225
01:20:36,207 --> 01:20:39,108
the fact that we're burning
all the fossil fuels,

1226
01:20:39,177 --> 01:20:42,340
in a few generations,
that we've wiped out the oceans,

1227
01:20:42,413 --> 01:20:44,404
that we've driven species
to extinction.

1228
01:20:44,482 --> 01:20:48,248
And worse - this is the worst part -
we know what we're doing.

1229
01:20:48,319 --> 01:20:50,014
The scientists know,
the environmentalists know,

1230
01:20:50,087 --> 01:20:52,385
the companies know
and the general public knows,

1231
01:20:52,456 --> 01:20:55,084
and yet we're allowing ourselves
to do it.

1232
01:20:57,562 --> 01:21:01,053
- Sharks have lived
in balance with the oceans

1233
01:21:01,131 --> 01:21:02,928
as the top predator.

1234
01:21:04,301 --> 01:21:07,862
Now we are the top predator,

1235
01:21:07,938 --> 01:21:10,771
deciding which species we'll use

1236
01:21:10,841 --> 01:21:13,207
and which we'll destroy.

1237
01:21:13,276 --> 01:21:16,643
I wonder if we've evolved enough

1238
01:21:16,713 --> 01:21:19,147
to survive as they have.

1239
01:21:22,919 --> 01:21:26,252
We depend on the oceans
for oxygen;

1240
01:21:26,323 --> 01:21:29,292
the oceans that sharks control.

1241
01:21:33,396 --> 01:21:35,261
If we lose sharks,

1242
01:21:35,332 --> 01:21:37,960
we'll disrupt the oxygen
we need to breathe.

1243
01:21:42,339 --> 01:21:45,706
We've only been here
for a few million years

1244
01:21:45,775 --> 01:21:47,867
and in the last 100 years,

1245
